1. Introduction
In the previous article, we learned how to create a default route and highlight the active navigation link using routerLinkActive.
In this article, we’ll learn two more important routing concepts:

• redirectTo

• Wildcard Route ('**')
These help us redirect users to the correct page and display a custom page when they enter an invalid URL.
2. What We Will Build
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Our application contains:

• Home

• About

• Contact

• Login

• Page Not Found
We’ll learn:

• Redirect /home to /

• Display a 404 page for invalid URLs
3. Create NotFound Component
ng generate component not-found4. Configure Routes
app.routes.ts
import { Routes } from '@angular/router';import { HomeComponent } from './home/home.component';
import { AboutComponent } from './about/about.component';
import { ContactComponent } from './contact/contact.component';
import { LoginComponent } from './login/login.component';
import { NotFoundComponent } from './not-found/not-found.component';
export const routes: Routes = [
{
path:'',
component:HomeComponent
},
{
path:'about',
component:AboutComponent
},
{
path:'contact',
component:ContactComponent
},
{
path:'login',
component:LoginComponent
},
{
path:'home',
redirectTo:'',
pathMatch:'full'
},
{
path:'**',
component:NotFoundComponent
}
];
5. What is redirectTo?
redirectTo automatically sends users from one route to another.
Example:
{
path:'home',
redirectTo:'',
pathMatch:'full'
}Now when a user opens
/homeAngular automatically redirects to
/6. Why do we use pathMatch: 'full'?
pathMatch tells Angular how to match the URL.
Example
{
path:'home',
redirectTo:'',
pathMatch:'full'
}full means Angular redirects only when the complete URL matches /home.
Without pathMatch:'full', Angular may redirect unexpected URLs.
7. What is Wildcard Route ('**')?
The wildcard route catches every URL that doesn’t match any defined route.
Example
{
path:'**',
component:NotFoundComponent
}If the user enters
/profileor
/abcor
/xyz123Angular displays the NotFoundComponent.
8. Create Not Found Page
not-found.component.html
<h1>404 - Page Not Found</h1><p>The page you are looking for doesn't exist.</p>
<a routerLink="">Go Back Home</a>
9. Import RouterLink
not-found.component.ts
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { RouterLink } from '@angular/router';@Component({
selector: 'app-not-found',
standalone: true,
imports: [RouterLink],
templateUrl: './not-found.component.html',
styleUrl: './not-found.component.css'
})
export class NotFoundComponent {
}
